# 2574. Left and Right Sum Differences

## Pattern

Prefix Sum | Suffix Sum | Space Optimization



## Problem

For each index i:

* Left Sum = sum of all elements before index i
* Right Sum = sum of all elements after index i

Find:

abs(Left Sum - Right Sum)

Example:

nums = [10,4,8,3]

Output:

[15,1,11,22]

---

## Brute Force Solution

### Intuition

For every index:

1. Traverse all elements before it to calculate leftSum.
2. Traverse all elements after it to calculate rightSum.
3. Store the absolute difference.

### Time Complexity

O(n²)

### Space Complexity

O(n)

### Code

```java
class Solution {

    public int[] leftRightDifference(int[] nums) {

        int n = nums.length;
        int[] ans = new int[n];

        for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {

            int leftSum = 0;
            int rightSum = 0;

            for(int j = 0; j < i; j++) {
                leftSum += nums[j];
            }

            for(int j = i + 1; j < n; j++) {
                rightSum += nums[j];
            }

            ans[i] = Math.abs(leftSum - rightSum);
        }

        return ans;
    }
}
```

---

## Better Solution (Prefix + Suffix Arrays)

### Intuition

Instead of recalculating sums repeatedly:

* Store left sums in a prefix array.
* Store right sums in a suffix array.

Then:

answer[i] = abs(leftSum[i] - rightSum[i])

### Time Complexity

O(n)

### Space Complexity

O(n)

### Code

```java
class Solution {

    public int[] leftRightDifference(int[] nums) {

        int n = nums.length;

        int[] ans = new int[n];
        int[] leftSum = new int[n];
        int[] rightSum = new int[n];

        leftSum[0] = 0;

        for(int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
            leftSum[i] = leftSum[i - 1] + nums[i - 1];
        }

        rightSum[n - 1] = 0;

        for(int i = n - 2; i >= 0; i--) {
            rightSum[i] = rightSum[i + 1] + nums[i + 1];
        }

        for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            ans[i] = Math.abs(leftSum[i] - rightSum[i]);
        }

        return ans;
    }
}
```

---

## Optimal Solution

### Key Observation

totalSum = leftSum + nums[i] + rightSum

Therefore:

rightSum = totalSum - leftSum - nums[i]

So we no longer need a suffix array.

### Intuition

1. Calculate totalSum.
2. Maintain leftSum while traversing.
3. Derive rightSum using:

rightSum = totalSum - leftSum - nums[i]

4. Compute answer.

### Time Complexity

O(n)

### Space Complexity

O(1)

### Code

```java
class Solution {

    public int[] leftRightDifference(int[] nums) {

        int n = nums.length;
        int[] ans = new int[n];

        int totalSum = 0;

        for(int num : nums) {
            totalSum += num;
        }

        int leftSum = 0;

        for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {

            int rightSum = totalSum - leftSum - nums[i];

            ans[i] = Math.abs(leftSum - rightSum);

            leftSum += nums[i];
        }

        return ans;
    }
}
```

---

## Key Learning

Whenever a problem asks:

* Sum before index
* Sum after index
* Left Sum vs Right Sum

Think:

1. Prefix Sum
2. Suffix Sum
3. Can one side be derived using Total Sum?

This often reduces space complexity from O(n) to O(1).
